            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kevin Lam is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog and its fusion of cultures. Born to a Hong Kong immigrant father who ran a small tailor shop in the Richmond and a second-generation Irish-American mother from the Sunset, Kevin\u2019s childhood was a blend of Cantonese proverbs and Catholic school discipline. He wasn\u2019t a scholar; he was practical, more interested in the city's streets than in textbooks. He learned the art of conversation and negotiation not in a debate club, but by watching his parents navigate a world that wasn't always built for them.\n\nForegoing a four-year university, he earned an Associate's degree from City College of San Francisco, a pragmatic choice that allowed him to enter the workforce quickly. He started as a bank teller, a position where his natural affability and sharp mind for numbers shone. He saw the mortgage loan officers with their client relationships and bigger commissions and knew that was his path. Without a prestigious degree, he outworked everyone, mastering underwriting guidelines and building a network of real estate agents who trusted his diligence. The 2008 financial crisis was his crucible; while others fled the industry, Kevin stayed, helping families navigate foreclosures and complex refinancing, an experience that hardened his resolve and cemented his reputation.\n\nNow 47, Kevin's life is a testament to his persistence. He lives in a clean, modern condo in Noe Valley, the result of a divorce a decade ago that left him with a quiet sense of melancholy and a fierce dedication to his daughter, now away at college. His routine is steady: a morning ride on the J-Church Muni line to his downtown office, a day of high-stakes deals, and an evening spent either at a Giants game or enjoying a quiet dinner in the Mission, a neighborhood he barely recognizes from his youth.\n\nKevin feels like a bridge between the old San Francisco and the new. He laments the city\u2019s astronomical cost of living but is also a beneficiary of its real estate market. His dreams are no longer about exponential wealth but about stability and connection. He hopes to earn a Vice President title before he retires, reconnect more deeply with his daughter, and maybe, finally, buy a small cabin near the Russian River. He is, in essence, the city itself: a mix of grit and ambition, forever tied to his roots while navigating a constantly changing landscape."
