        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s ten, breathing in the scent of steamed wool and chalk in his father\u2019s Richmond shop. His father switches from rapid-fire Cantonese with a customer to careful, measured English for his mother. Kevin sees it clearly: his parents are translators, constantly navigating different worlds. He didn't learn the art of negotiation from a book; he learned it on that stool, realizing that the key wasn't what you said, but how you made someone feel understood. It became the bedrock of his career.\n\n2.\nHe remembers sitting in a macroeconomics class at City College, listening to classmates talk about transferring to Cal. He felt a sting of inadequacy, but it was quickly replaced by a cold, practical clarity. Their path was four more years of theory; his was getting a paycheck next month. That afternoon, walking to his bank teller job, he decided he wouldn't resent them. He would simply outwork them. The chip on his shoulder wasn't anger; it was fuel.\n\n3.\nIt was 2009, the nadir of the crash. An elderly couple, the Garcias, sat crying in his cubicle, foreclosure papers trembling in their hands. They\u2019d lived in their Excelsior home for forty years. While other lenders saw a defaulted loan, Kevin saw their life\u2019s work about to evaporate. He spent weeks fighting for a modification he eventually won. The victory didn't feel like a commission; it felt like a moral imperative. That day forged his grit and gave his work a purpose that wealth alone never could.\n\n4.\nThe divorce was just paperwork until he packed the last box in their Sunset house around age 37. It was late, and his young daughter, Maya, was asleep. He stood in her doorway, watching her small chest rise and fall, and the silence of the house felt immense, crushing. A profound melancholy settled into his bones that night, a quiet grief he still carries. But with it came a fierce, singular focus: everything from that moment forward would be for her.\n\n5.\nHe stood on the platform after dropping Maya off at SFO for college. He watched the J-Church pull away, the same train he took to work every day, but this time it felt hollow. The silence that awaited him in his Noe Valley condo was no longer just the quiet of a bachelor pad, but the profound emptiness of a finished chapter. It was then his ambition shifted once more\u2014from providing for her to truly connecting with her, a new and far more complex deal to close."
